english:
  title: The Tale of the Sluggard
  author: Sung Kan
  language: eng
  text: |-
    There was a man known as the Sluggard, though none could say from whence he came. In all his endeavors, idleness reigned supreme, and so the world called him thus. He rose to the rank of Direct Attendant among the unranked officials. His home held five thousand volumes, yet he never opened a single page. His head festered and his body broke out in sores, yet he could not be troubled to seek cure. Indoors he found sitting burdensome; on the road, walking itself. Like a wooden doll he stood, vacant and hollow. His household despaired, consulting shamans and offering prayers, all to no avail.

    Then came Keen-hearted Scholar, newly learned and burning with noble purpose to save mankind. He came with his teachings, hoping to transform the Sluggard, who sat sprawled before him, hair loose, eyes wide with vacant stare, consumed by his lethargy. Keen-hearted Scholar proclaimed: "Since ancient times, men live by diligence and perish by sloth. Thus the sages guard themselves through industry. King Wen had no leisure as the sun declined; Yu the Great treasured every inch of time. Nor is this mere human virtue—the wind and rain, frost and snow, cycling through the seasons, nurturing all things: this is Heaven's diligence. Heaven may be learned from, but never defied. To defy Heaven brings calamity."

    The Sluggard smiled, waving him away: "It is I who should teach you, not you me. A man lives but a hundred years, body and spirit alike worn thin by toil. By day he labors without rest, from dawn to dusk in ceaseless rushing, doing all that may be done. By night he sleeps fitfully, mumbling in dreams until morning comes again. What profit in this? The true sage does not live thus." And seizing his staff, he drove Keen-hearted Scholar out.

    But Keen-hearted Scholar pondered long, then smiled: "Now I know the way." He filled a vessel with wine, enlisted a fair companion, and choosing his moment, approached the Sluggard saying: "Today the breeze is gentle and warm, birds sing in the mountains. Come, let us share in joy and revelry."

    The Sluggard's eyes brightened. He cast off his robe and rose—so quickly that his shoes found the threshold and his staff touched the road almost before he could move. Decades of indolence dissolved in an instant. Together they raised their cups in great merriment, and from that day forth, the Sluggard lived in diligence.
  footnotes:
    - Keen-hearted Scholar (勤須子) represents the Confucian virtue of industriousness confronting natural human tendency toward ease.
    - The references to King Wen and Yu the Great are classical exemplars of virtuous labor—King Wen worked until sunset, and Yu the Great was so devoted to his duties that he passed his own home three times without entering.
    - The tale employs a philosophical debate typical of Korean Neo-Confucian literature, where direct persuasion fails but indirect approach through sensory pleasure succeeds, suggesting that virtue may be awakened rather than imposed.
